<subSubSection lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,1749,2029]" lastBlockId="26.[151,1436,153,683]" lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,420,1821,1848]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Description. Male.</emphasis>
Whole fly as 
<figureCitation box="[579,676,1821,1848]" captionStart="FIGURES 165–172" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[174,1416,203,1904]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[156,1432,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 165–172. Megaselia khaghaniniai Namaki &amp; Disney n. sp. male. 165, whole fly; 166, frons; 167, detail of frons; 168, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 169, outer half of abdomen; 170, left face of epandrium; 171, epandrium and anal tube; 172, hypandrium and penis complex. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573414" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573414/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 165</figureCitation>
. Frons as 
<figureCitation box="[790,886,1822,1848]" captionStart="FIGURES 165–172" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[174,1416,203,1904]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[156,1432,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 165–172. Megaselia khaghaniniai Namaki &amp; Disney n. sp. male. 165, whole fly; 166, frons; 167, detail of frons; 168, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 169, outer half of abdomen; 170, left face of epandrium; 171, epandrium and anal tube; 172, hypandrium and penis complex. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573414" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573414/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 166</figureCitation>
, with dense but very fine microtrichia (
<figureCitation box="[1332,1428,1822,1849]" captionStart="FIGURES 165–172" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[174,1416,203,1904]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[156,1432,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 165–172. Megaselia khaghaniniai Namaki &amp; Disney n. sp. male. 165, whole fly; 166, frons; 167, detail of frons; 168, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 169, outer half of abdomen; 170, left face of epandrium; 171, epandrium and anal tube; 172, hypandrium and penis complex. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573414" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573414/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 167</figureCitation>
) and notable for the lower supra-antennal bristles being as long as the upper pair, which are further then the pre-ocellar bristles, and the anterolaterals being well above the antials which are situated close to the eye margins. Cheek with a single bristle and jowl likewise but it is longer and more robust. Postpedicels brown, without SPS vesicles, the yellow palps and proboscis as 
<figureCitation box="[540,637,1966,1992]" captionStart="FIGURES 165–172" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[174,1416,203,1904]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[156,1432,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 165–172. Megaselia khaghaniniai Namaki &amp; Disney n. sp. male. 165, whole fly; 166, frons; 167, detail of frons; 168, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 169, outer half of abdomen; 170, left face of epandrium; 171, epandrium and anal tube; 172, hypandrium and penis complex. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573414" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573414/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 168</figureCitation>
, the labella with only a few short hairs/spinules below. Thorax brown. With 3 notopleural bristles and no cleft in front of these. Mesopleuron bare. Scutellum with an anterior pair of small hairs and a posterior pair of bristles. Abdominal tergites brown with small hairs hairs, but 1–2 longer ones at sides of T2 and at rear of T6; and venter paler brown with hairs on segments 3–6. Hypopygium as 
<figureCitation box="[1176,1331,189,215]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 165–172" captionStart-1="FIGURES 173–176" captionStartId-0="28.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionStartId-1="29.[151,264,924,949]" captionTargetBox-0="[174,1416,203,1904]" captionTargetBox-1="[174,1423,187,886]" captionTargetId-0="figure@28.[156,1432,181,1920]" captionTargetId-1="figure@29.[151,1436,181,898]" captionTargetPageId-0="28" captionTargetPageId-1="29" captionText-0="FIGURES 165–172. Megaselia khaghaniniai Namaki &amp; Disney n. sp. male. 165, whole fly; 166, frons; 167, detail of frons; 168, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 169, outer half of abdomen; 170, left face of epandrium; 171, epandrium and anal tube; 172, hypandrium and penis complex. Scale bars 20 μm." captionText-1="FIGURES 173–176. Megaselia khaghaniniai Namaki &amp; Disney n. sp. male. 173, right face of hypopygium; 174, front tarsus; 175, hind femur and tibia; 176, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573414" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573416" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/3573414/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/3573416/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Figs 169–173</figureCitation>
, the hairs on epandrium being smaller than those at rear of tergite 6, on cerci and proctor apart from one posterolaterally that is more robust than rest and longer than the hairs of procter. The hypandrial lobe of the right side is vestigial. Legs yellow apart from dark tip to hind femur. Fore tarsus slender with postero-dorsal hair palisades on segments 1–5 (
<figureCitation box="[160,257,333,359]" captionStart="FIGURES 173–176" captionStartId="29.[151,264,924,949]" captionTargetBox="[174,1423,187,886]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1436,181,898]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 173–176. Megaselia khaghaniniai Namaki &amp; Disney n. sp. male. 173, right face of hypopygium; 174, front tarsus; 175, hind femur and tibia; 176, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573416" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573416/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 174</figureCitation>
). Dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia extends about 0.58 times its length. Hairs below basal half of hind femur longer than those of the anteroventral row (
<figureCitation box="[640,739,368,395]" captionStart="FIGURES 173–176" captionStartId="29.[151,264,924,949]" captionTargetBox="[174,1423,187,886]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1436,181,898]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 173–176. Megaselia khaghaniniai Namaki &amp; Disney n. sp. male. 173, right face of hypopygium; 174, front tarsus; 175, hind femur and tibia; 176, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573416" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573416/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 175</figureCitation>
). Hind tibia with 10 differentiated posterodorsal hairs with all but the basal 2 robust (
<figureCitation box="[404,500,404,431]" captionStart="FIGURES 173–176" captionStartId="29.[151,264,924,949]" captionTargetBox="[174,1423,187,886]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1436,181,898]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 173–176. Megaselia khaghaniniai Namaki &amp; Disney n. sp. male. 173, right face of hypopygium; 174, front tarsus; 175, hind femur and tibia; 176, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573416" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573416/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 175</figureCitation>
), without anterodorsals, and spinules of apical combs simple. Wings (
<figureCitation box="[1277,1372,405,432]" captionStart="FIGURES 173–176" captionStartId="29.[151,264,924,949]" captionTargetBox="[174,1423,187,886]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1436,181,898]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 173–176. Megaselia khaghaniniai Namaki &amp; Disney n. sp. male. 173, right face of hypopygium; 174, front tarsus; 175, hind femur and tibia; 176, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573416" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573416/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 176</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.32" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" unit="mm" value="2.32">2.32 mm</quantity>
long. Costal index 0.49. Costal ratios 3.34: 2.31: 1. Costal cilia (of section 3) 
<quantity box="[1080,1180,441,467]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" unit="mm" value="0.09">0.09 mm</quantity>
long. No vein 3 hair. 2 unequal axillary bristles, the outermost being 
<quantity box="[664,764,477,503]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" unit="mm" value="0.14">0.14 mm</quantity>
long. Sc not reaching R1. Haltere brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,153,683]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,349,512,539]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Recognition.</emphasis>
In the key to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1856" box="[543,660,513,539]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[543,660,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Megaselia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males of the British Isles (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[958,1103,513,539]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref21228" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle Flies-Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects, 10 (8), 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 203, where each lead only applies in part. In 
<bibRefCitation author="Borgmeier, T." box="[522,742,549,576]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" pagination="1 - 160" refId="ref20965" refString="Borgmeier, T. (1966) Revision of the North American Phorid flies. Part III. The species of the genus Megaselia, subgenus Megaselia (Diptera, Phoridae). Studia Entomologica, Petropolis, 8, 1 - 160. [1965]" type="journal article" year="1966">Borgmeier’s (1966)</bibRefCitation>
key to Nearctic Group VII it runs to couplet 37 lead 
<specimenCount box="[1333,1385,549,575]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="generic">
1 
<taxonomicName authority="(Coquillett)" authorityName="Coquillett" baseAuthorityName="Coquillett" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[1354,1385,550,575]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fungicola">
<emphasis box="[1354,1385,550,575]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">M.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</specimenCount>
fungicola (Coquillett) but its lower supra-antennal bristles are much shorter and finer than the upper pair and its wing is less than 
<quantity box="[281,367,620,647]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
long.
</paragraph>
